### FQ-PIE
* **Presenter:** **Mohit P. Tahiliani**
* **Draft Referenced:** `draft-ietf-tsvwg-fq-pie`
* **Slides Referenced:** [FQ-PIE](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-tsvwg-fq-pie-01)
* **Discussion:**
  * FQ-PIE has been implemented in Linux, FreeBSD, and NS3, and is being actively deployed by Quantum Networks in customer access points in India.
  * Recent hackathon testing focused on FQ-PIE vs. FQ-CoDel in mobile hotspot environments. Results consistently demonstrated superior 90th percentile tail latency for FQ-PIE due to its drop-on-enqueue design, which mitigates tail latency when queues build up.
  * **Chris Box** asked whether these performance differences are consistent across non-Wi-Fi environments. **Mohit P. Tahiliani** confirmed that NS3 simulations across varied network environments (published in CNSM) show consistent benefits. **Greg White** added that CableLabs previously documented similar performance advantages for the base PIE algorithm compared to CoDel during DOCSIS standardization.
  * L4S support for FQ-based active queue management (AQM) mechanisms will be addressed in a separate draft to avoid complicating the core FQ-PIE document.
  * A patch implementing per-flow statistics collection for Linux has been submitted to Net-Next.

