### L4Sops Draft and L4S Interoperability
* **Presenter:** **Greg White**
* **Draft Referenced:** `draft-ietf-tsvwg-l4sops`
* **Slides Referenced:** [L4Sops Draft and L4S Interops](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-tsvwg-l4sops-draft-and-l4s-interops-01)
* **Discussion:**
  * Recent hackathon testing assessed WebRTC Screen integration, Netflix NDTC ingestion, and Static Rate Management (SRM).
  * A new proposal for implementing L4S in core switches using a Two-Rate Three-Color Marker (TRTCM/SRM) was written as a separate draft by Kuhn de Schepper. Greg updated `draft-ietf-tsvwg-l4sops` to reference this new work.
  * **Miroslav Kos** (co-author of the SRM draft) explained that this method provides a valuable alternative for high-speed core gateway devices shaping to access lines where absorbing large bursts is inefficient.
  * **Martin Duke** raised a concern that SRM does not strictly relate to RFC 3168 coexistence, which is the core scope of the `draft-ietf-tsvwg-l4sops` document. **Greg White** clarified that while its scope is broader, it remains highly relevant for operators migrating from classic ECN.
  * **Gory Fairhurst** and **Zaheduzzaman Sarker** suggested parking the WGLC of the L4Sops draft to allow the working group time to review and mature the SRM draft.
  * A poll was taken on whether to wait for the SRM draft or ship L4Sops immediately: 8 voted to wait, 14 voted to ship. 

